Part I - PISA 2012¶

by Philipp Nockemann¶

Introduction¶

In this notebook i am going to explore the PISA 2012 dataset. This dataset is the result of PISA study. This study examines how well students have learned the school curriculum, how well prepared they are for life beyond school. Around 510,000 students in 65 economies took part in the PISA 2012 assessment of reading, mathematics and science. Of those economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy.

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

Sorted by Country there is one row for each student. In the survey the students were asked about motivational, financial an other circumstances that could influence their results of the mathematic and science assessment. There are categorical variables als well as numerical ones.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

There are many features of interest in the dataset. A passionate didact could try to make sense of special weaknesses and strengths in different problem types by other factors like country, gender or self concept. A social worker could try and investigate socioeconomic impacts on motivation. The vastness of the dataset allows a broad bandwidth of approaches.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

As a maths teacher in a german school, out of 600+ columns i am mainly interested in parental factors and the kind of factors that I or we as an educational institution could influence. Also national differences and gender specific questions arose when I looked at the data. The choice is arbitrary though because there ar many more interesting features in the PISA study.

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

Observation 1: The initial automatic distribution of final scores is highly right skewed. There are relatively very few results above 250 but some are even much higher than that. To get a sense of the distribution you should limit both axes.

Observation 2: There seem to be a lot of students with a score of 0 or close to 0. This observation is difficult to interpret which is why I I limited the x-axis to a score of 50 or higher. I found out there were kind of different local modes in the distribution with one mode close to 0, the next around 75, another around 130 and yet another one around 170/180. The peaks tend to get smaller so the distribution as a shape that looks like four waves getting smaller consecutively.

Observation 3: Countries with most participants are Mexico, Italy, Spain, Canada, Brazil. Most countries have around 5000 participants. Choosing representative samples I assume 5000 to be enough to get valid results, even for large countries. Maybe the countries with large numbers did this for national study purposes.

Oberservation 4: There are slightly more girls than boys in the dataset. This should overall be a good representation since there are more women than men in the world.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I tried a log-scaled score-axis in the first visualisation which reveals a kind of tri-modal distribution with peaks on 0 Points and 10-30 Points. These are difficult to interpret to me. Thus i did'nt draw any meaningful observation from the log-scaled histogram.

I had to adjust bins and axis limits for the second final score distribution. Otherwise one could hardly see the multimodal structure of the distribution.

I had to bring the value counts of the countries in order and enlarge the figure. Without ordered value counts it's harder to see which countries have the most participants and that many countries have almost equally many participants.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. How did the feature(s) of interest vary with other features in the dataset?¶

Observations #5 - #9: Since there are many final student weights close to zero, which is hardly interpretable, i played around a lot with the ranges of final student scores i wanted to accept for comparison with parents socioeconomic background. I cannot display all of the ranges i tried and different ranges almost always led to different observations. Still i found a couple of interesting obersvations: First, almost all ranges i tried showed a relatively low score of students whose parents' ISCED level is "3B, 3C", which is the highest educational level in the data. Second, there is a correlation between parents' job status "Other" and high scores. Looking for an explanation for the latter i guess "Other" might include entrepreneurs and "self-made" people, which could mean there are quite a lot upper class students. Third, students with full-time working parents have relatively bad scores. Getting more or less support by parents at home might have an effect!

Obersvation #10: Visualization #10 shows - interestingly - that if parents strongly agree that mathematics is important, students are worse than if parents only "Agree". Too much pressure influencing students learning behaviour in several possible ways here might be an issue.

Observation #11: The heatmap in Visualization #11 (coloring is log-scaled) clearly shows how a general sense of belonging to school is correlated to final score. While most students don't feel strongly belonging to school, those who do clearly have better chances of scoring well than those who don't.

Observations #12 - #17: Finally visualizations #12 - #17 show how teachers specific engagements correlate to a general sense of belonging to school. Most effective means are encouraging to reflect problems and giving the opportunity to express opinions. It seems to me that those are the features which mostly support a good relationship between students an teachers which might be an explanation for the observation. Overall the six features are part of broader teacher-related features we can find in the original dataset: "Teacher Behaviour: Formative Assessment", "Teacher Behaviour: Student Orientation", "Teacher Behaviour: Teacher-directed Instruction" and "Teacher Support".

Did you observe any interesting relationships between the other features (not the main feature(s) of interest)?¶

I did not find any observable difference in scores of males and females.

Visualization #18: What impact on final scores do a sense of belonging to school and student oriented teaching have?¶

In [21]:
#Define number of bins for 2d-histogram
belong_min = pisa12['Sense of Belonging to School'].min()
belong_max = pisa12['Sense of Belonging to School'].max()
belong_binwidth = (belong_max - belong_min)/7

teach_min = pisa12['Teacher Behaviour: Student Orientation'].min()
teach_max = pisa12['Teacher Behaviour: Student Orientation'].max()
teach_binwidth = (teach_max - teach_min)/7

bins_x = np.arange(belong_min, belong_max+belong_binwidth, belong_binwidth)
bins_y = np.arange(teach_min, teach_max+teach_binwidth, teach_binwidth)

pisa12_bt = pisa12[pisa12['Sense of Belonging to School'].notnull()
                   & pisa12['Teacher Behaviour: Student Orientation'].notnull()
                   & pisa12['Final student score'].between(10, 500)]


# Determine which bin for each point
belong_bins = pd.cut(pisa12_bt['Sense of Belonging to School'], 
                     bins_x, right = False, 
                     include_lowest = False, 
                     labels = False).astype(int)
teach_bins = pd.cut(pisa12_bt['Teacher Behaviour: Student Orientation'], 
                    bins_y, right = False, 
                    include_lowest = False, 
                    labels = False).astype(int)

# Count the points in each bin
n_points = pisa12.groupby([belong_bins, teach_bins]).size()
n_points = n_points.reset_index().pivot(index = 'Sense of Belonging to School', columns = 'Teacher Behaviour: Student Orientation').values

# Divide final scores by the number of points in each bin
student_score_weights = pisa12_bt['Final student score'] / n_points[belong_bins, teach_bins]

plt.hist2d(data=pisa12_bt, 
           x='Sense of Belonging to School', 
           y='Teacher Behaviour: Student Orientation', 
           bins=[bins_x, bins_y],
           cmin=0,
           cmap='viridis',
           weights=student_score_weights
           )

plt.colorbar(label='Average Final score')
plt.xlabel('Sense of Belonging to School')
plt.ylabel('Teacher Behaviour: Student Orientation')
plt.title('Pisa 2012 education study')

def myPointPlot(df, 
                xVar = 'Relation - Teachers Listen to Students', 
                yVar = 'Final student score', 
                hue = 'Relation - Teachers Treat Students Fair', 
                color = 0, 
                palette = 'Greens', 
                order = accordance_order, 
                hue_order = accordance_order, 
                figsize = [14, 6],
                ax = None, 
                title = ''):
    '''
    parameters: df : data to be plotted
                xVar : df-column for x-axis
                yVar : df-column for y-axis
                hue : df-column to be colored
                color : element in  seaborn standard color_palette, single color for the elements in the plot
                palette : seaborn color_palette for hue
                order : order for (categorical) xVar
                hue_order : order for (categorical) hue
                figsize : size for figure if not ax
                ax : number of subplot
                title : title of single pointplot
    
    output: pointplot with parameters (optionally as subplot)
    '''
    
    if not ax:
        # set plot dimensions
        plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
        ax=plt.gca()
        
    # plot
    sb.pointplot(data=df, x=xVar, y=yVar, hue=hue, color=sb.color_palette()[color],
                 palette=palette, order=order, hue_order=hue_order, ax=ax,
                 linestyles='', dodge = 0.3, errorbar=('ci', 90));
    
    # AFTER plotting, clean up variable names 
    xVar=xVar.replace("_", " ") # replace _ with a space 
    yvar=yVar.replace("_", " ") # replace _ with a space
    
    if hue:
        hue=hue.replace("_", " ")
    # Add title and format it
    ax.set_title(f'''{title}'''.title(), fontsize = 10, weight = "bold" )
    # Add × label and format it
    ax.set_xlabel(xVar.title(), fontsize = 8, weight = "bold")
    # Add y label and format it
    ax. set_ylabel(f'Average {yVar}'.title(), fontsize = 8, weight = "bold" )

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

Observation #18 - #19: Heatmap: The visualizations showed that there is some (not a lot) synergy between student oriented teaching and 'Sense of belonging to school' respectively disciplinary climate. Especially the combination of a positive disciplinary climate and student orientation seems to lead to good results rather than low scores in these features. We have to qualify that medium scores in these features lead to good results as well.

Observation #20: I couldn't find strong patterns regarding the reciprocal impact of parents' job statuses, out-of-school study time and students' results. Students whose parents work part time or 'Other' (home-duties, retired etc.) seem to study somewhat longer out-of-school than the others. Also those students whose parents are looking for a job seem to score the least.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

Observation #21: There is some interesting obersvation here. For scores of students who don't feel like they belong to school, fairness matters on every level of teacher's listening ability. In contrast, on the higher levels of Sense of belonging, fairness only matters to those who don't feel heard. Being listened to has a bigger impact here. These differences could not be observed in bivariate exploration.

Conclusions¶

  • In my exploration i began showing some distributions which are always present in media publications on PISA study.

  • Bivariate barplots showed impacts of socio-economic backgrounds of parents on students scores. Surprisingly children of people with highest schooling scored worse than others.

  • A 2D-Histogram showed that almost no students that feel like they don't belong to school could score high in PISA study. This emphasizes the importance of making school a space of identification for everything.

  • Numerous Boxenplots make us understand that teachers can influence student's senses of belonging to school by student-oriented behaviour. Most important are encouraging students to reflect problems and giving them the opportunity to express their opinion.

  • Multivariat heatmaps showed: Especially the combination of a positive disciplinary climate and student orientation seems to lead to good results rather than low scores in these features. We have to qualify that medium scores in these features lead to good results as well.

  • A faceted scatterplot of parent's job status, out-of-school study time and PISA scores couldn't reveal any clear pattern between those three features.
  • Pointplots relating four features showed: For scores of students who don't feel like they belong to school, fairness matters on every level of teacher's listening ability. In contrast, on the higher levels of Sense of belonging, fairness only matters to those who don't feel heard. Being listened to has a bigger impact here.
